  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Systematic Cost Analysis (SCAN) Tool</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Humanitarian needs far outweigh the resources to meet them: In 2017 only 50% of HRP appeals were met, leaving a gap of $11.6 billion. Spending money to deliver the most life-saving assistance is critical, but at present we are unable to answer questions like, &#x201C;How much should I budget to meet these needs? Could I save more lives by implementing a different program design?&#x201D; To answer such questions, humanitarian actors would need to run a customized analysis on not only their program, but on other comparable programs to determine the best course. In emergency settings, hardly anyone has the time&#x2014;or the specialized skills&#x2014;to perform such a feat. The Systematic Cost Analysis (SCAN) Tool addresses this urgent need for data by making the production of cost analysis data faster and more rigorous than ever before, enabling humanitarian actors to confidently identify strategies that will deliver the most life-saving aid within limited budgets.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The main objective of this projects is to develop a multi-agency version of the SCAN tool that works with the data systems of main humanitarian agencies, and successfully generates high-quality value for money evidence. SCAN will increase the reach and effectiveness of life-saving assistance delivered within limited humanitarian budgets. While SCAN can be applied to any sector of programming, initial focus will be on generating cost data and developing &#x201C;Value for Money&#x201D; lessons in 3 areas where appetite for cost evidence is highest: Cash, Education &amp; Nutrition. 1. Main results will include: bringing together major humanitarian actors to adapt and, on an ongoing basis, govern the SCAN tool; 2. Building a multi-agency version of SCAN which conducts rapid, rigorous cost analysis and can be configured to work with the finance system of most major humanitarian actors; 3. Adoption of SCAN at major humanitarian agencies, and introduction of resulting cost evidence into sectoral coordination groups.</narrative>
  </description>
